===Etymology 1===
Dialectal variant (akin to {{etyl|sv|-}} dialect {{term|natt-batta|lang=sv}}) of {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bakke|lang=enm}}, {{term|balke|lang=enm}}, from Scandinavian (compare Old {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|natbakka|lang=sv}}, Old {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|nathbakkæ}} 'night-flapper', {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|leðrblaka|lang=non}} 'leather-flapper').

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# Any of the small, [[nocturnal]], flying [[mammal]]s of the order [[Chiroptera]], which navigate by means of [[echolocation]]. They look like a mouse with membranous wings extending from the forelimbs to the hind limbs or tail. Altogether, there are about 1,000 bat species in the world.
#* '''2012''', Suemedha Sood, <tt>(bbc.co.uk)</tt> [http://www.bbc.com/travel/blog/20120209-travelwise-texas-love-bats Travelwise: Texas love bats] [sic]
#*: ''As well as being worth millions of dollars to the Texan agriculture industry, these mammals are worth millions of dollars to the state’s tourism industry. Texas is home to the world’s largest known [[bat]] colony (in Comal County), and the world’s largest urban [[bat]] colony (in Austin). '''Bat''' watching is a common activity, with the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department offering more [[bat]]-viewing sites than anywhere else in the US.''
# {{context|offensive}} An old woman.
# {{1811}} A low whore: so called from moving out like a bat in the dusk of the evening.

